\title{Cosmological model with dynamical curvature}
\author{Peter C. Stichel\\
Fakult\"at f\"ur Physik, Universit\"at Bielefeld\\
D-33501 Bielefeld, Germany\\ 
e-mail: peter@physik.uni-bielefeld.de}
\date{02.02.2016}

\maketitle


\begin{abstract}
We generalize the recently introduced relativistic Lagrangian darkon fluid model (EPJ C (2015) 75:9) by starting with a self-gravitating geodesic fluid whose energy-momentum tensor is dust-like with a nontrivial energy flow. The corresponding covariant propagation and constraint equations are considered in a shear-free nonrelativistic limit whose analytic solutions determine the 1st-order relativistic correction to the spatial curvature. This leads to a cosmological model where the accelerated expansion of the Universe is driven by a time-dependent spatial curvature without the need for introducing any kind of dark energy. We derive the differential equation to be satisfied by the area distance for this model.
\end{abstract}


\section{Introduction}
There is no doubt that the present universe undergoes a phase of accelerated expansion (cp. [1]) and the literature cited therein). Almost all of the observations are in good agreement with the $\Lambda$-cold dark matter (CDM) cosmology [2]. But some observations are in disagreement with this $\Lambda$CDM model (see [3]). And from the theoretical point of view we do not know of any convincing solution for the well-known ``Cosmological constant problem'' (cp. [2], [4] ). As alternatives to the $\Lambda$CDM model two different strategies are under discussion in the physics community. In the first category one introduces some kind of new physics by changing Einsteins field equations (EFEs). In principle the $\Lambda$CDM model belongs to this category as the introduction of a cosmological constant modifies the original EFEs. In the second category one considers in the framework of the old physics the accelerated expansion as an apparent effect due to the averaging over inhomogeneities in the Universe (for a recent review see [5]). To the first category belong alternative cosmological models which explain the accelerated expansion and/or dark matter by changing either the geometrical part of Einsteins field equations (EFEs) (called modified gravity; see [6], [7] and the literature cited therein) or by changing the matter part by adding some scalar fields (for a recent review see [8]). But all these proposals are of a phenomenological nature, they contain either some unknown parameters or even some freely chosen functions. To overcome such a freedom we need some new (i.e. nonstandard) physics which, however, should be based on known fundamental physical principles (e.g. symmetry). Such an attempt has been made quite recently by the present author and W. J. Zakrzewski [9]. Based on General Relativity (GR) we introduced a Lagrangian model, containing no unknown parameters, which led to an energy-momentum tensor  consisting of a dust term and a nontrivial energy flow.

Hence our model belongs to the class of models with a modified matter part of the EFEs. The model is a GR- generalization of the nonrelativistic darkon fluid model introduced in [10], further developed in [11, 12] and reviewed and extended in [13]. The guiding principle of this model is the unextended Galilei algebra, dynamically realized by a fluid consisting of massless Galilean particles minimally coupled to gravity.This fluid we have called darkon fluid as it has been introduced initially for the description of the dark sector of the Universe.  But, as argued in [9], the solution manifold contains also the baryonic matter as dust. The nonrelativistic model describes successfully the transition from a decelerating to an accelerating phase of the Universe as well as the Hubble function and the flat behavior of galactic rotation curves [10, 13]. But within the nonrelativistic framework we have not been able to discover the physical mechanism which is behind the transition from a decelerating to an accelerating phase. Initially we have tried to understand our results in terms of some dynamical dark energy (repulsive gravity determined by a negative pressure) [13].  However this is totally misleading as we have learned by now from the relativistic treatment.  We have found that at sub-Hubble scales the relativistic model reproduces the nonrelativistic results but with a new physical interpretation:  The present-day  cosmic acceleration is not attributed to any kind of dark energy (negative pressure) but it is due to a dynamically determined negative spatial curvature [9].  But due to the restricted validity of the sub-Hubble scale approximation we could not use this interpretation up to or beyond the transition point between decelerating and accelerating phase.  In the present paper we extend this result as far as a nonrelativistic description of the Universe is permitted. 

We will start in section 2 with a Lagrangian-free generalization of our relativistic model which contains as ingredients a self-gravitating irrotational and geodesic  fluid whose dynamics is determined by an energy-momentum tensor consisting only of an energy density term and a nontrivial energy flow vector. Restricting to the conformal flat case we discuss in section 3 the corresponding covariant propagation and constraint equations for the kinematic quantities. In section 4 we tackle first the problem of vanishing resp. small fluid shear. This limit turns out to be discontinuous. The two limits, the shear-free resp. nonrelativistic limit, are not interchangeable. So the shear-free nonrelativistic limit has to be defined by taking the two limits in a definite way simultaneously . We will show that the leading terms of our equations in this limit contain a nontrivial and computable 1st--order relativistic contribution to the spatial curvature (which, however, vanishes in leading order). In section 5 we state the cosmological equations and derive their analytic solutions. These solutions are already known from our former work [10]-[13], but now they are given in terms of the dynamically determined spatial curvature. 

Due to the non-vanishing energy flow we cannot use the FLRW-formula for the angular diameter distance $D_A$. In section 6 we derive the differential equation to be obeyed by $D_A$ for our model as well as analytic expressions for the corresponding coefficient-functions.  Some concluding remarks are presented in section 7.



